# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-borne-bomb-attacks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] From April through June 1919, a series of bombings were carried out or attempted across the United States by Galleanists (followers of Italian insurrectionary anarchist Luigi Galleani).
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The targets included anti-immigration politicians, anti-anarchist officials, and prominent businessmen, as well as a journalist and a church.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Almost all of the bombs were sent by mail.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The bombings were one of the major factors contributing to the First Red Scare.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Two people were killed, including one of the bombers, and two injured.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] In late April 1919, at least 36 booby trap dynamite-filled bombs were mailed to a cross-section of prominent politicians and appointees, including the Attorney General as well as justice officials, newspaper editors and businessmen, including John D.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The mail bombs were wrapped in brown paper with similar address and advertising labels.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Inside, wrapped in bright green paper and stamped "Gimbel Brothers-Novelty Samples", was a cardboard box with a 6 by 3 by 1 inch (150 by 80 by 30 mm) block of hollowed wood, packed with a stick of dynamite.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] A small vial of sulfuric acid was fastened to the wood block, along with three fulminate-of-mercury blasting caps.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Opening one end of the box (the end marked "open") released a coil spring that caused the acid to drip from its vial onto the blasting caps; the acid ate through the caps, igniting them and detonating the dynamite.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The Galleanists intended their bombs to be delivered on May Day.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Since 1890 and the Second International, May 1 had been celebrated as the international day of communist, anarchist and socialist revolutionary solidarity.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Seattle Mayor Ole Hanson, who had recently attained national prominence for opposing a general strike in Seattle, received one of the mailed package bombs, but it was opened by William Langer, a member of his office staff.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Langer opened the wrong end of the box and the bottle of acid dropped onto a table without detonation.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] He took the bomb to the local police, who notified the Post Service and other police agencies.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Hardwick, who had co-sponsored the Alien Anarchists Exclusion Act of 1918, received a similarly disguised bomb.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] It blew off the hands of his housekeeper when she attempted to open the package.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The senator's wife was also injured in the blast, which severely burned her face and neck and a piece of shrapnel cut her lip and loosened several of her teeth.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] News reports of the Hardwick bomb described its distinctive packaging and an alert post office employee in New York connected this to 16 similar packages which he had set aside a few days earlier for insufficient postage.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Another 12 bombs were eventually recovered before reaching their intended targets.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] On the evening of June 2, 1919, the Galleanists managed to detonate nine large bombs nearly simultaneously in eight cities.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] These bombs were much larger than those sent in April, using up to 25 pounds (11 kg) of dynamite and all were wrapped or packaged with heavy metal slugs designed to act as shrapnel.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Addressees included government officials who had endorsed anti-sedition laws and deportation of immigrants suspected of crimes or associated with illegal movements, as well as judges who had sentenced anarchists to prison.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Palmer, who had already been the recipient of a mail bomb in April, was again attacked in the new wave of violence.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Though not seriously injured, Palmer and his family were shaken by the blast and the house itself was largely demolished.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Two near-casualties of the same bomb were Assistant Secretary of the Navy Franklin Delano Roosevelt and his wife Eleanor, then living across the street from Palmer.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] They had passed the house just minutes before the explosion and their residence was close enough that one of the bomber's body parts landed on their doorstep.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The flyer was later traced to a print shop operated by two anarchists, typesetter Andrea Salsedo and compositor Roberto Elia, who were both Galleanists according to the later memoirs of other members.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Salsedo died under suspicious circumstances (either by suicide or defenestration depending on the source) was and Elia refused an offer to cancel deportation proceedings if he would testify about his role in the Galleanist organization.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Unable to secure enough evidence for criminal trials, authorities continued to use the Anarchist Exclusion Act and related statutes to deport known Galleanists.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Fueled by labor unrest and the anarchist bombings, and then spurred on by Attorney General A.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Mitchell Palmer's attempt to suppress radical and non-radical labor organizations, the response to the bombings was characterized by exaggerated rhetoric, illegal search and seizures, unwarranted arrests and detentions and the deportation of several hundred suspected radicals and anarchists.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Palmer, twice targeted by anarchist bombs, organized the nationwide series of police actions known as the Palmer raids in November 1919 and January 1920.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Under suspicion of violating the Espionage Act, the Sedition Act and/or the Immigration Act of 1918, approximately 10,000 people were arrested, of whom 3,500 were held in detention.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Of those held in detention, 556 resident aliens were eventually deported.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The bombings were dramatized in the 2012 film *No God, No Master.* The bombing of the home of Palmer was also dramatized in the 2011 film *J.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The June Bombings and the "Plain Words" fliers were referenced in the video game *Arkham Origins* by Anarky, one of the game's antagonists.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] By January 2012, about 15 journalists were affiliated with *+972*, and most wrote in English for a largely American audience.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The website has an "unorthodox journalistic ethos: All the website's bloggers have complete freedom to write whenever and whatever they want".
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] Sarah Wildman, writing in *The Nation* in early 2012, says the magazine is "purposefully, uniformly progressive".
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] According to Leibovitz, *+972* reporters are well-positioned to report from the West Bank.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] Several members of the cooperative are "frequent participants in joint Israeli–Palestinian demonstrations behind the Green Line", and work closely with "the activists who coordinate such protests".
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In 2016, *+972* was sued by Sawsan Khalife, its former chief executive officer, alleging that her dismissal was racially motivated.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In its statement of defense, *+972* denied the allegation, claiming Khalife was dismissed due to ever increasing dissatisfaction in her professional conduct.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The parties settled their dispute in Tel Aviv Regional Labour Court, agreeing that the Court will award Khalife between 2.5 and 7 salaries worth of compensation as well as other benefits, while also agreeing that each side will withdraw its claims.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The Court awarded Khalife 39,000 New Israeli Shekels.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In a joint investigation by *+972 Magazine* and the Hebrew-language outlet *Local Call*, it was revealed that Microsoft's Azure cloud platform was being used by Unit 8200, Israel's elite spy agency.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The report disclosed a secret project to transfer large volumes of sensitive intelligence into Azure, which began after a 2021 meeting between Microsoft's CEO Satya Nadella and the unit's commander.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The investigation found that the collaboration enabled Unit 8200 to build a system that collected, played back, and analyzed the content of millions of cellular calls from the entire population of Gaza and the West Bank.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] This surveillance data, which amounted to as much as 8,000 terabytes, was held in a Microsoft data center located in the Netherlands.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The report also highlighted that this cloud-based platform was utilized in the Gaza offensive to prepare for airstrikes.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] Following the publication of the joint investigation, Microsoft launched an external inquiry.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] This inquiry resulted in the tech giant terminating Unit 8200's access to some of its cloud storage and AI services.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The magazine is largely financed by reader contributions.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In addition, the Heinrich Böll Foundation, a German think-tank affiliated with the German Green Party, provided 6,000 euros in first-year funding in 2010.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] According to *The Nation*, the Social Justice Fund at the New Israel Fund granted *+972* $10,000 in the first year, and made a one-year grant of $60,000 in early 2012.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] Between 2018 and 2021, *+972* and its partner, *Local Call*, received $450,000 from the Open Society Foundations.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The website's staff state that the vast majority of *+972*'s readers live outside Israel, with about 40% in the United States and 20% in the Palestinian territories.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] According to CEO Noam Sheizaf, about 20% of its readership are Israeli.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] Israeli left-wing politicians Akiva Eldar and Merav Michaeli told *The Nation* that Israelis were mostly unaware of the existence of *+972*, with Michaeli describing it as simply "not relevant" to Israeli politics.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In 2012, according to *The Nation*, writers for the left-wing newspaper *Haaretz* and left-wing Israeli intellectuals believed that the new web magazine fills an important gap in Israeli media reporting, primarily focusing on settlements and human rights abuses against Palestinians.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The same year, the Israeli right-wing NGO Monitor accused *+972* of being antisemitic due to its reporting on Israeli apartheid.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] When I fight for the right of an Arab woman to become a doctor, you will stand by and donate to the New Israel Fund.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In 2025, the Nieman Foundation for Journalism awarded *+972* the Louis M.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] Lyons Award for Conscience and Integrity in Journalism, celebrating the magazine's integrity to facts despite danger and adversity.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] In 2016, *Local Call* ran an exclusive on a Jerusalem cinema complex that refused to work with cab drivers of Palestinian ethnicity, a story picked up by leading newscaster Channel 2.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/972-magazine] The site also published the "License to Kill" series, which examined cases in which IDF soldiers shot and killed Palestinians without a clear provocation, and with no consequences for the soldiers, a type of incident that usually goes unreported in Hebrew-language mainstream media.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] Projects of bat bombs, dog bombs, and pigeon bombs have also been studied.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] In 2009, Taliban insurgents strapped an improvised explosive device to a donkey and let the donkey loose a short way from a camp of the British Armed Forces in Helmand Province.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] In April 2013, in Kabul, a bomb attached to a donkey blew up in front of a police security post, killing a policeman and wounding three civilians.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] A government spokesman claimed insurgents were challenging the competence of the Afghan government prior to the 2014 withdrawal of the U.S. military.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] On 21 November 2003, eight rockets were fired from donkey carts at the Iraqi oil ministry and two hotels in downtown Baghdad, injuring one man and causing some damage.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] In 2004, a donkey in Ramadi was loaded with explosives and set off towards a US-run checkpoint.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] It exploded before it was able to injure or kill anyone.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The incident, along with a number of similar incidents involving dogs, fueled fears of terrorist practices of using living animals as weapons, a change from an older practice of using the bodies of dead animals to hold explosives.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The use of improvised explosive devices concealed in animals' carcasses was also a common practice among the Iraqi Insurgency.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] Malia Sufangi, a young Lebanese woman, was caught in the Security Zone in November 1985 with an explosive device mounted on a donkey with which she had failed to carry out an attack.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] She claimed that she had been recruited and dispatched by Syrian Brigadier-General Ghazi Kanaan who supplied the explosives and instructions on how the attack was to be carried out from his headquarters in the town of Anjer in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] In 1862, during the New Mexico campaign of the American Civil War a Confederate force approached the ford at Valverde, six miles north of Fort Craig, hoping to cut Union communications between the fort and their headquarters in Santa Fe.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] When it was nearly midnight, Union Captain James Graydon tried to blow up some rebel picket posts by sending mules loaded with barrels of fused gunpowder into the Confederate lines; however, the mules went back toward the Union camp and detonated there.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] Although the only casualties were two mules, the explosions stampeded a herd of Confederate beef cattle and horses into the Union's lines, so depriving the Confederate troops of some much-needed provisions and horses.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] In the Wall Street bombing of 1920, an incident thought to be related to the 1919 United States anarchist bombings, anarchists used a bomb carried by horse-drawn cart.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] One method described by Helm has attracted attention for its illustration of what has been dubbed a 'rocket cat' – a feline with what appears to be a rocket on its back propelling it towards a castle or fortified town.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The same illustration also shows what appears to be a rocket-propelled dove.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The illustration appears in various forms in different manuscript versions of Helm's book, as well as in the 1625 printed edition.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The images appear in a section titled "To set fire to a castle or city which you can't get at otherwise," in which Helm describes ways of using incendiary devices strapped to animals to set fortified places on fire.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] During World War II the U.S. investigated the use of "bat bombs", or bats carrying small incendiary bombs.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] During the same war, Project Pigeon (later Project Orcon, for "organic control") was American behaviorist B.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] Skinner's attempt to develop a pigeon-guided missile.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The project was barely funded and was cancelled on 8 October 1944.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] They had also used incendiary bat bombs that were largely ineffective.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] At the same time the Soviet Union developed the "anti-tank dog" for use against German tanks.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The anti-tank dog project mostly failed, as the dogs would be spooked by the noises and gunfire, as well as running under Russian tanks due to the dogs being trained with diesel tanks, as opposed to the German tanks, which ran on petrol.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] The Imperial Japanese Army had used dogs and other animals strapped with bombs to run into American lines during Iwo Jima and Okinawa.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] More recently, Iran purchased several dolphins, some of which were former Soviet military dolphins, along with other sea mammals and birds, in what some have alleged to be an attempt by Iran to develop *kamikaze dolphins*, intended to seek out and destroy submarines and enemy warships.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] However, the animals are today on display at the Kish Dolphin Park, on Iran's resort island of Kish in the Persian Gulf.
[src:animal-borne-bomb-attacks/animal-borne-bomb-attacks] During the Cold War, the Soviet Navy trained dolphins to attach underwater explosives and beacons to ships and submarines at Object 825 GTS at Balaklava, Crimea.
